# Go Coding Agent CLI — Implementation Plan

## Context

We're building a Go implementation of a coding agent CLI, based on the architecture found in two Rust reference implementations: `claw-code-rust` (8-crate modular design) and `claudecode` (monolithic runtime). Both are clean-room rewrites of the Claude Code agent harness pattern.

The core idea: an LLM-powered CLI that takes user input, sends it to an LLM, executes tool calls the LLM requests (bash, file read/write, grep, glob), feeds results back into the conversation, and repeats until done. The **test harness as a feedback loop** is the most important architectural pattern — it makes the entire system testable without hitting real LLM APIs.

**Reference files studied:**
- `claw-code-rust/crates/core/src/query.rs` — The query loop (384 lines, the heart of the system)
- `claw-code-rust/crates/core/tests/harness/mod.rs` — ScriptedProvider, SpyTool, EventCollector
- `claw-code-rust/crates/core/tests/harness/builders.rs` — Test scenario builders
- `claw-code-rust/crates/core/tests/L1_basic_loop.rs` — 10 baseline tests
- `claw-code-rust/crates/tools/src/orchestrator.rs` — Tool execution (concurrent/sequential)
- `claudecode/rust/crates/runtime/src/conversation.rs` — Alternative runtime with hooks

